Name_@footnote: FY18-FY22 cost per quantity variation is due to variation in multiple Type/Model/Series (T/M/S) platform aircraft, platform quantities, associated equipment per platform, and cost per equipment. ** B-Kit quantities differ from A-Kits where B-Kits consist of a card or module that will be integrated without A-Kit requirement.   ** Installation Kit/Installation Equipment quantities reflect number of units procured, installation quantity reflects number of aircraft. ** Certifications are based on analysis and do not necessarily reflect integration. ** Production Lead Time is acceptable and does not impact induction of aircraft due to length of aircraft modification. ** FY18-FY20: The A-Kit recurring growth is due to MH-60R/S, MH-53E and AV-8B Required Navigation Performance Area Navigation (RNP RNAV) and H-1 Series, F/A 18 A+, F-5, F-16, KC-130T, T-38 and AV-8B to achieve Automatic Dependent Surveillance - Broadcast (Out) (ADS-B Out) compliance by January 1st, 2020 as mandated in Title 14 CFR Parts 91.225 and 91.227. ** To explain prior year delta, FY12 PMA209 procured the A-Kits for (5) P-3A Aircraft and PMA290 funded the correlating (5) P-3A aircraft installs.
FY18: Leveraging an Air Force Contract for the Non-Recurring Engineering that has to occur before Procurement in FY19.

FY18-FY22: The B-Kit Recurring growth is due to H-1 Series, F/A-18 A-D, F-16, F-5, KC-130J, and KC-130T  to achieve Automatic Dependent Surveillance - Broadcast (ADS-B Out), AV-8B, MH-53E and MH-60 R/S to achieve Required Navigation Performance Area Navigation (RNP RNAV).  **FY18, PMA209 will procure (54) F/A-18 A-D Combined Interrogator Transponder (CIT) Mode S upgrade B-Kits, no A-Kit or install required for CIT Mode S upgrade kits. **FY19, PMA209 will procure (42) F/A-18 A-D CIT Mode S upgrade B-Kits, no A-Kit or install required for CIT Mode S upgrade kits.

Costs for obsolescence kits vary because obsolescence issues are not an ongoing effort for a single item and are not subject to inflation driven increases.  The requirement for obsolescence kits was determined by evaluating historic life of type buy costs for analogous systems. These costs were projected to support future obsolescence issues in the affected components.  Obsolescence efforts have been underfunded for the past, causing the program to reallocate current-year budget to cover emergent obsolescence mitigation efforts per Resource Sponsor direction.  The increases from year to year are necessary to recover from several years of shortfalls.

Costs for obsolescence kits vary because obsolescence issues are not an ongoing effort for a single item and are not subject to inflation driven increases.  The requirement for obsolescence kits was determined by evaluating historic life of type buy costs for analogous systems. These costs were projected to support future obsolescence issues in the affected components.  Obsolescence efforts have been underfunded for the past, causing the program to reallocate current-year budget to cover emergent obsolescence mitigation efforts per Resource Sponsor direction.  The increases from year to year are necessary to recover from several years of shortfalls.

F/A-18 A-Kit:   During FY 2017 thru FY 2020 A-kits are being procured for F/A-18C 2-dispenser, F/A-18D 2-dispenser, and F/A-18D 4-dispenser configurations.  The A-kit components and unit costs vary, depending on which type, model, series (TMS) being modified and quantity of dispensers (2 or 4 each) per TMS.  The FY 2019 cost increase was driven by additional F/A-18Ds becoming available for Air Frame Change (AFC)-566, which requires (4) dispensers and requires increased hours to complete modification.  Commander, Naval Air Forces (CNAF) is continuing extension of flight hours and service life on the F/A-18s, possibly to FY 2031, to fill strike fighter shortfall, requiring additional aircraft modifications.    FY19 Congressional action reduced FY19 funded installations from (25) to (15) aircraft. FY20 added (5) retrofit installations creating a new To-Complete quantity of (29) for the planned aircraft modifications to accommodate F/A-18 aircraft with extended service life. To Complete Cost increase for installations is due to remaining installations being F-18D four (4) dispenser configuration which increases both hardware and labor installation above prior two (2) dispenser aircraft configurations.

F/A-18 B Kits: FY 2019 B-Kit cost increase is due to procurement of new B-kit components (prior year B-kit components were reused or reconditioned from retiring aircraft with ALE-47 installed). B-kit unit cost and the component quantities vary depending on aircraft configuration: D model aircraft have (4) dispensers vice (2) for C model aircraft. The Technical Directive for AFC-566 was approved to allow for stand-alone modifications, which provides increased schedule flexibility ALE-47 Retrofit aircraft induction without schedule delays of concurrent aircraft modifications. FY20 added (5), leaving a Cost-To-Complete quantity of (29) for the planned aircraft modifications to accommodate F/A-18 aircraft with extended service life. To Complete Cost increase for installations is due to remaining installations being F-18D four (4) dispenser configuration which increases both hardware and labor installation above prior two (2) dispenser aircraft configurations.

DI Full Motion Video (FMV) supports Urgent Universal Needs Statement (UUNS) CDTS# 11061UA.  The separation of DI-FMV was made to reflect a phase 1 which includes a 2 tail-mounted antennas and a carry-on ANW2 waveform capability, which provides an interim capability to meet the UUNS.

The separation of DI-FMV was made to reflect a Phase 2 due to the increased costs associated with adding an additional antenna to provide FMV coverage forward of the aircraft, and integrating the ANW2 waveform capability as a permanent solution.

The UH-1Y is only equipped with the legacy APR-39D(V)2 system. Increase in FY 2020 with the modification of (10) UH-1Y's allows the Marine Corps the flexibility to deploy aircraft with a common digital processor type, that will enhance situational awareness, enhance effectiveness and suitability in complex, hostile environments in support of Marine Expeditionary Operations.

Name_val: 2.1.1) BRITE Star BLK II Laser Spot Tracker (UH-1Y) - NonOrganic
2.1.2) Target Sight System (TSS) Block Upgrade (AH-1Z) - Organic
Name_@footnote: The USMC H-1 Operating Forces Capabilities Planning Document identifies the need for an electro-optical system capable of automatically detecting laser designator energy for purposes of target handoff operations. The Target Sight System (TSS) Block Upgrade includes the TSS Laser Spot Tracker, Turret Electronic Unit, and High Definition upgrade to enable the AH-1Z to detect, acquire, and track laser designator energy for more expeditious target handoff and engagement. Procurement of equipment begins in FY 2020.

Increase in FY 2019 Installation Equipment N/R (material, engineering and test) required for Target Sight Sensor (TSS) Block Upgrade. Without the N/R TSS block upgrade will be forced to continue utilizing the current TSS which has deficiencies that impact AH-1Z situational awareness and reduces the capability in the employment of the Joint Air To Ground Missile (JAGM) scheduled to IOC in FY 2020.

Name_@footnote: Readiness increase in FY 2018 for (160) Inverters will impact readiness of the UH-1Y Fleet significantly. Existing UH-1Y inverters are currently experiencing high rates of failure (low reliability) which is having a negative effect on the readiness of the UH-1Y Fleet. Reports show these inverters have a Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) average of 263 hrs. The new DSP-type inverter calculated MTBF is 3,468 hrs. Replacing old inverters with new DSP-type inverters increases time between replacement by ~3,205 hours per unit. Contract award slipped from FY17 to FY18.
